@Styromaniac: They ace at different things because they're philosophically opposed. ZN is about decentralized hosting of websites. IPFS tries to create universal links for content that never updates. With ZN updatability of the site is in mind when building. In IPFS the opposite is true.

Amusingly, despite ZN being mutable and IPFS being immutable, we end up with ZN having more redundancy due to it's opt-out nature rather than IPFS's opt-in nature.

To me the clear winner appears to be ZN. IPFS can barely function half the time.

